## Overview

This issue hit me when I was implementing support for custom `validate_doc_read` functions (written in both native Erlang and JS), because `validate_doc_update` is not sufficient for our production use case.

When you implement `validate_doc_update` as an Erlang function it doesn't work because of a missing case clause, namely: when `couch_query_servers:try_compile()` calls `ddoc` in the `couch_native_process` for a native `validate_doc_update` the return value may be an atom `ok` or `true` but in case of JS function we have `1`. I added an additional guard check for all these situations in the `validate_doc_update` and now it works for Erlang functions as well. 

## Testing recommendations

Implement `validate_doc_update` as Erlang function in the design doc (`"language": "erlang"`), run CouchDB with `--enable-erlang-views` and update some docs in the db in order to trigger this call.

